TI  - Adaptive learning in international business
JO  - Journal of International Business Studies
SP  - 1547
EP  - 1567
VL  - 51
IS  - 9
AB  - Building on Daniel Levinthal’s seminal theories on learning, adaptation, and innovation, this article elucidates an adaptive view of organizational learning undertaken by multinational enterprises (MNEs). Levinthal’s perspectives have tremendous implications for theorizing and examining processes, pathways, and mechanisms of dynamic learning for MNEs competing in a complex environment. This article extends these perspectives, considering unique organizational traits and environmental characteristics facing MNEs for a more nuanced understanding of contexts in which adaptive learning creates global competitive advantage. Discussion also includes Levinthal’s perspectives that are not yet adequately extended to, but valuable for, IB research, such as learning mindfulness, cognitive search, organizational architecture for adaptation, and co-evolution with technological change. We offer additional research questions as well as possible solutions to adaptive learning for international business.
